125 of 277 patients (

 45.1%

) experienced pain in the lidocaine group, compared with 123 of 229 patients (

 53.7%

) in the Balanced Salt Solution group. The proportion of patients who experienced pain was significantly lower in the intracameral lidocaine group compared with the Balanced Salt Solution group (multivariate OR 0.68, 95% Confidence Interval 0.47 to 0.97; p=0.034). The median pain score (range) was 0.0 for intracameral lidocaine group compared with 1.0 for Balanced Salt Solution group (p=0.039). Pain was more common in females (54.3% versus 43.6%; OR 1.56), non-Chinese (62.3% versus 46.9%; OR 2.13) and those who had previous cataract surgery to the fellow eye (55.3% versus 44.7%; OR 1.61).
